gradually completed in Rijeka during the 2020 Rijeka ‚Äì Euro-pean Capital of Culture project. This included the reuse of in-dustrial buildings for the Museum of Modern and Contempo-rary Art (by architect Dinko Peraƒçiƒá), and the reconstruction of the Sugar Refinery Palace for the City Museum of Rijeka (by architect Irma Huiƒá), the brick house for the Children‚Äôs House (by architect Sa≈°a Randiƒá), and, finally, the T building for the City Library (by architect Sa≈°a Randiƒá). Rijeka, the cradle of industry and industrial archaeology of Croatia, is enriched by this exceptional cultural block.\nMUSEUMS AND EXHIBITIONS In 2025, the Museum of the City of Zagreb held an exhibi-tion entitled 1947‚Äì1952 Ideology and Planned Industrialisa-tion (Goran Arƒçabiƒá). In Sisak, the restoration of the Dutch House in the former grain warehouse was completed, and the building is now home to the first Centre of Industrial Heritage in Croatia.\n82 CROATIA Reconstruction of the former steam mill complex Paromlin in Zagreb to house a city library and community center (UPI-2M) (photo by author) In Dubrovnik, a well-visited Museum of Red History was opened in the former TUP factory of Carbon Graphite Prod-ucts. It was a bottom-up realisation, spontaneously followed by the conversion of the factory into a co-working space, libraries, etc.\nThe current nominations for Croatia‚Äôs most important ar-chitectural awards, awarded by the Association of Croatian Architects (UHA), indicate a valuable refocusing on industrial heritage and its revalorisation, from two aspects. Two Zagreb designs secured the nominations focused on reusing industrial complexes: the Slaughterhouse (Klaonica, architects Filip and Kre≈°imir Romiƒá) and the Container (Kontejner), located in the former part of the Vjesnik publishing house (SKROZ). On the other hand, due to a series of changes in global relations, the theme of reindustrialisation is also noticeable in the nominations for the UHA awards: the Rimac Campus electric car production facility (3LHD), and the production and office building in Dubrovƒçan (MVA).\nTRAINING AND EDUCATION INITIATIVES Industrial archaeology is included in study programmes at the Faculty of Architecture of the University of Zagreb. It is also taught, in condensed form, at the Faculty of Civil Engineering of the University of Rijeka, the Faculty of Civil Engineering, Architecture and Geodesy of the University of Split, and the Faculty of Civil Engineering and Architecture of the J.J. Strossmayer University of Osijek. Numerous graduation theses done in all four study programmes focus on the resto-ration and reuse of industrial heritage.\nSOCIAL AND COMMUNITY-BASED PROJECTS Following the conversion of a part of the mining complex in Labin into the Public Library in Labin (arch. Ivana ≈Ωalac, Margita Grubi≈°a, Igor Preseƒçan and Damir Gamulin), the re-GENERATOR - Center of Urban Culture was built follow-ing the project by MVA architects by transforming the former Regeneracija factory. Spontaneous use of the old industrial warehouse for concerts resulted in forming a new youth centre in the former industrial zone.\nPUBLICATIONS ‚Ä¢ Bjelanoviƒá, A.; Paliniƒá, N.; Frankoviƒá, M. (2022) Struc-tures of the First Industrial Age in Rijeka, Croatia ‚Äî from Timber to Iron. Industrial Archaeology Review, 44(1); 19-35. ‚Ä¢ Bari≈°iƒá Mareniƒá, Z. (2025): Industrijska arhitektura [In-dustrial Architecture]. Portal hrvatske tehniƒçke ba≈°tine, Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle≈æa, Hrvatska tehniƒçka enciklopedija, Zagreb.\n83 CROATIA re-GENERATOR - Centre for Urban Cul-ture (MVA) in Zabok (photo by author) Ploƒçe,a modern planned port and industrial city in the south of Dalmatia (pho-to by author) ‚Ä¢ Kranjƒçeviƒá, J.; Bari≈°iƒá Mareniƒá, Z.; Jelƒçiƒá, D. (2024). Urban Genesis of a Modern Port-Industrial Town on the Adriatic from 1945 to 1990 - Ploƒçe, Croatia/Prostor: znanstveni ƒçasopis za arhitekturu i urbanizam, 32(2); 294-307.\n‚Ä¢ Matan, C.; Bari≈°iƒá Mar